This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. Today we're beginning a three-part series on
science fiction author Lee Killow. Killow is a Kansas native who wrote several

00:51.800 --> 01:01.260
short stories during the 1970s, then produced four novels in short order in the
1980s. She began as a writer of hard science fiction, but here we find out how

01:01.260 --> 01:10.820
she converted to the more character-oriented variety. I started out, and my
interest was mostly in really hard science fiction. I was a die-hard analog

01:10.820 --> 01:23.780
reader. And the first story I ever sold was to analog, and it was an analog kind
of story. I haven't sold a story to analog since. Almost everything I've written

01:23.780 --> 01:33.760
since has come out in, the majority of it has come out in fantasy and science
fiction. I've had one in Galileo and a couple in If magazine before it folded.

01:35.220 --> 01:44.000
But I got more and more interested in people and realizing that hardware wasn't
the thing, that it was people, and that people were interesting and what made

01:44.000 --> 01:57.180
them tick. And so the more I started researching that, the more I got interested
in what makes society to click. And then when I started making up aliens and I

01:57.180 --> 02:06.080
started reading a lot of anthropology to figure out really how societies go
together, the more I read, the more I researched, the more fascinated I got.

02:07.320 --> 02:16.120
Killow goes to great lengths to keep the details of her books consistent. Listen
as she explains how she is able to keep track of the minutiae. I put together a

02:16.120 --> 02:25.900
background book before I ever start the novel itself. It's an amount of work
that I know some people find exhausting.

02:26.740 --> 02:38.360
They couldn't do it and still have any energy left to write the book. But I
enjoy it. I'm very systematic. I start out with a lot of visual images in my

02:38.360 --> 02:49.100
head. And with vague visual images, you have to have them developed to a very
clear, you have to develop a very clear image, and you have to find the words

02:49.100 --> 02:58.620
for them and get them translated into actual words out of pictures before you
can get them down on paper. So I do a background book, and I do maps of the

02:58.620 --> 03:13.200
planet, and I do drawings of the flora and fauna and biographies of the people.
And the more I read on climatology and planetology, the more complex backgrounds

03:13.200 --> 03:24.820
get. It takes me about the same amount of time to put a background together, but
it gets much more complicated. Now they're almost as thick as the final

03:24.820 --> 03:34.500
manuscript on the book. Writers have many reasons for plying their trade. Killow
has an interesting point of view on the role and rewards of writers, including

03:34.500 --> 03:49.020
herself. A writer is entertaining. And if he thinks that he's creating deathless
prose with every line he struggles to put down, and if he's writing for history,

03:50.260 --> 04:03.780
then he's probably got pretensions of grandeur. If I write a book that people
buy and read by buying, they give me my money, which I need, and if they enjoy

04:03.780 --> 04:17.120
it by reading it, then I'm really happy. I don't think I would write a book just
for money, but certainly I want to write something that is fun for me to write,

04:17.160 --> 04:26.480
and I want to write something that is fun for readers to read. Killow's work
seldom end with all's well and they lived happily ever after. She believes that

04:26.480 --> 04:38.900
life is fraught with problems. There are a lot of large social problems that
exist within each book that never get solved, but people in the books solve

04:38.900 --> 04:47.300
their own problems. They handle their own lives. And I think maybe that, a
little bit of personal philosophy of mine, comes through that I can't solve the

04:47.300 --> 04:58.600
world's problems, but I can certainly keep control of my own life. And my belief
in that I can pass on. Join us tomorrow as we look at a few of Lee Killow's

04:58.600 --> 04:59.020
novels.

