the unlikely title The Monitor, The Miners, and The Shree. It differs from the
works we discussed previously in that it is set in another future history, one

12:40.940 --> 12:51.280
called The Sodality. Listen as Killough talks about the origins and the
inhabitants of this universe. That's a future history that I was working on as a

12:51.280 --> 12:59.640
teenager, which started out as very peaceful and wonderful and tended to get
much more complex and much more violent. The older I got, the more I realized

12:59.640 --> 13:08.520
that people just didn't get along with each other all the time. I have several
short stories that are set in that particular universe. And I'll probably come

13:08.520 --> 13:17.260
back to it again. It's an interesting one because it has a lot of different
groups, none of which are human, and offers possibilities for societies and

13:17.260 --> 13:28.540
interplays. And aliens. See, the future history I have set up, the one that most
of the novels are in, has a minimal of aliens before we actually have all run

13:28.540 --> 13:42.000
across one, which is spacing. And then, of course, there's aliens that are on
the planet on which the colonists

13:42.000 --> 13:48.460
who are in trouble on the Invictus land, the book I'm working on at the moment,
has some aliens on it. But there's a minimal of aliens. And if I want to deal

13:48.460 --> 13:59.640
with alien species, it's just really easy to go to that other future history,
which has all kinds of aliens running around. I like to think of it as just

13:59.640 --> 14:07.140
being across, being on our same galaxy, it's just on the other side, you know,
way out of contact with us, probably not where we're likely to run into it very

14:07.140 --> 14:15.880
soon. The plot of the Monitor the Miners and the Shree is centered about the
fact that representatives of the Department of Surveys and Charters are sent to

14:15.880 --> 14:24.860
monitor the world Naira, a proscripted world, for any signs of progress among
primitive inhabitants, the Shree. The team discovers that a corporation by the

14:24.860 --> 14:34.180
name of Imra has been actively mining the planet for 500 years, an action
strictly forbidden by the sodality. The last chapter of the novel is a courtroom

14:34.180 --> 14:44.200
scene. We ask Killua if her husband, Pat, who happens to be a lawyer, offered
her any advice on its content. In fact, the lawyer half-wrote that particular

14:44.200 --> 14:50.380
chapter. He was telling me, oh, this character ought to say that, and then you
ought to bring up this point, and then you ought to bring counter with that

14:50.380 --> 15:03.800
legal point. And the whole chapter definitely got submitted to him for scrutiny
as procedure and logical thinking. So he's half the creator of that last

15:03.800 --> 15:14.480
chapter. Recently, a book of Kelo's short stories appeared under the name
Aventine. This is a collection of loosely connected stories all set in the city

15:14.480 --> 15:24.620
of Aventine, a cultural and fine arts center. The stories are told from a first
-person point of view. We asked Killua why she chose this approach. I like those

15:24.620 --> 15:36.840
particular stories from a first-person point of view because you can understand
then, the storyteller is always victimized in some way in those particular

15:36.840 --> 15:37.400
stories.

15:54.860 --> 16:04.660
Besides writing, singing, drawing, dancing, and theater are artistic influences
in Kelo's background. It was this experience that helped inspire her to write

16:04.660 --> 16:16.640
the Aventine stories. We asked her how the ideas developed. Most of those
stories came out of images. There'd be like one single image.

16:21.240 --> 16:31.800
I like the image of a pair of footprints, scarlet and sand, going away. The
image just kept with me and kept with me until I found a story to go with it.

16:33.200 --> 16:37.740
Lee Killua was a dedicated, conscientious writer from whom we can expect more
fine work.

