it during the summer. I was teaching in New York.

19:09.060 --> 19:19.700
And there, what I wanted to do with that book was make a strong anarchist
statement about the way I found it in society. It was, you know, like, basically

19:19.700 --> 19:31.320
sort of the late 60s. Even though it was in the mid-70s. Rucker was unable to
sell Space Time Donuts immediately. Here he tells us the story behind his very

19:31.320 --> 19:43.560
successful White Light. The way I came to write White Light was kind of weird. I
wrote Space Time Donuts and I couldn't sell that anywhere. And finally Unearthed

19:43.560 --> 19:56.140
Magazine agreed to serialize it. And they serialized the first two parts of it.
And they went out of business. And at that point I lost my job when I was

19:56.140 --> 20:08.700
teaching in upstate New York. They wouldn't give me 10 years of dance. It was
different. But then I got a grant to go to do mathematics in Germany. And I got

20:08.700 --> 20:17.760
a grant from the German government. Went to Heilberg. Went there for, I had a
two-year, well, a two-year grant there. And it's from the Son Humboldt

20:17.760 --> 20:21.280
Foundation. That's why some of my books are dedicated to Humboldt.

20:23.640 --> 20:32.960
And I got over there. And to my delight, I discovered that the person in charge
of my research really didn't care about mathematics either. And so I just

20:32.960 --> 20:43.020
started writing science fiction. And I spent about three months trying to solve
this problem, continuum problem. And I thought, you know, I knew a lot about it.

20:43.240 --> 20:51.280
It's a very difficult problem. And then I said, well, I'm just going to write a
novel about it. And then I came to write White Light that way. Which, it's about

20:51.280 --> 20:59.300
a different level of infinity. The packaging of an American edition of White
Light made it appear as though the book were another in a long line of life

20:59.300 --> 21:10.120
-after-life books. We asked Rucker how this came about. Well, that was Jim Bain.
He was the editor at Ace at that time. And he bought it. I was happy that he

21:10.120 --> 21:18.680
bought it. You know, he gave me good money. And it was just his marketing
decision. He probably thought, well, we can film more copies if we package it

21:18.680 --> 21:31.760
as, you know, something for sort of superstitious, foolish people. Instead of
packaging it as avant-garde literature. And I imagine he's probably right. We

21:31.760 --> 21:40.740
asked Rucker if he had any input on the packaging. Well, the one thing I got
them to put on the cover was, do you want to see God? I got them to put that on

21:40.740 --> 21:49.960
the back. We asked Rucker how people who bought the book, thinking it was a
straight life-after-life novel, reacted to it. Well, I've met people since then

21:49.960 --> 22:00.700
that are really into, like, dream stuff and astral travel. Like, they've read it
very seriously and they're just like, don't understand why the book is sort of

22:00.700 --> 22:05.180
not so serious as it should be. More on Rudy Rucker on our next show.

