talk to you. And that was like an experience that usually you would only get it
once because God, you'd look out for it at other times. That's very White Light.

24:22.920 --> 24:30.480
Rucker's third novel, Software, is written in a more conventional style than
were White Light and Space Time Donuts. It differs from these two in another

24:30.480 --> 24:40.480
aspect as well. The software I was trying something different because in a way
both Space Time Donuts and White Light are autobiographical. They're both

24:40.480 --> 24:51.860
essentially the main, the hero that's me. And then I wanted to see if I could do
a book where I wasn't in it. And so in software, there's like a young guy who's

24:51.860 --> 25:04.600
sort of, you know, based on a guy that I used to hang around with, a guy younger
than me. And the old guy in there is, to an extent, based on my father. In

25:04.600 --> 25:12.760
software, a simulacrum of the famous mathematician Gertle makes a brief
appearance to lecture on Gertle's incompleteness theorem. This theorem says that

25:12.760 --> 25:20.960
humans cannot build robots as intelligent as themselves. Rucker had several
discussions with Gertle shortly before Gertle died. Listen as he describes the

25:20.960 --> 25:32.320
relationship. For me, he was like the ultimate guru that I ever met in my life.
And I just, you know, I was fortunate, you know, I got to see the master at that

25:32.320 --> 25:44.640
formative stage in my life. And again, that tends to be a one-time thing. I
mean, at this point, he's dead. And, you know, when I'm an old man, maybe

25:44.640 --> 25:55.100
somebody will come see me or something. But I don't expect to meet anybody like
that again. I think about Gertle, when you talk to him, when I talk to him, I go

25:55.100 --> 26:04.460
to make up a list of questions I want to ask him about all this stuff. About
math and philosophy and physics and so on. And, like, he'd been sitting alone in

26:04.460 --> 26:14.060
Princeton there, like, for 30 years. Like, 30 years ago, he had proved the
heaviest things that anybody had ever done in mathematics. He'd been, like, 30

26:14.060 --> 26:23.180
years past that. He was, like, thinking all the time. And anything I'd ask him,
you know. Like, he'd already been all the way down the road. And he would just

26:23.180 --> 26:31.460
laugh. I mean, a lot of when I would talk to him, he'd say a few words and then
he'd start laughing. And I'd start laughing with him. And, like, as we would

26:31.460 --> 26:40.420
laugh, I would feel like we were communicating. It was, uh, I mean, it sounds
kind of stupid when I say it like this. But, uh, it was, you know, like a real

26:40.420 --> 26:49.660
feeling of telepathy almost. Like, you know, anything I would say you would
totally understand. And it was just really, uh, unquestionably the greatest

26:49.660 --> 26:59.740
person I've ever made. The German philosopher Hegel is Rucker's several times
-removed grandfather. We asked him if there is any of Hegel's influence in his

26:59.740 --> 27:11.220
work. I think I've done my part, you know, for the absolute. It's, I really, I'd
like to read his stuff, and it's pretty hard to read. I've read books about him,

27:11.280 --> 27:21.720
but the actual books are very hard to read. But it's my impression that I have,
uh, somewhat the same ideas about, uh, the absolute. Uh, the absolute being the

27:21.720 --> 27:33.140
ultimate thing, the white life. And, uh, I would say, you know, like, later if
people look back, they'll say, well, gee, you know, it's pretty much what Hegel

27:33.140 --> 27:42.480
would have wanted to write if he was a science fiction writer. Rudy Rucker, the
